The @file{tools} directory in the mpatrol distribution contains two files called
@file{heapdiff.c} and @file{heapdiff.h} which demonstrate the use of
@code{__mp_snapshot()} and @code{__mp_iterate()} to find localised memory leaks.
Have a look at these files to see a further example of using these functions,
or perhaps even add these files to your application for debugging purposes.
Note that it is perfectly safe to allocate memory in the callback function used
by @code{__mp_iterate()}, and such allocations can be freed as well.  The only
restriction is that the callback function should never free a memory allocation
that it has not allocated itself.

An alternative way to detect differences in the heap between two points in a
program's execution is to make use of the leak table.  This is a hash table that
stores the number and size of memory allocations and deallocations referenced
by the source file and line number where they occur@footnote{If that information
is not available then the function name or return address will be used
instead.}.  The leak table can be cleared with a call to
@code{__mp_clearleaktable()} and can be displayed with a call to
@code{__mp_leaktable()}, which will display a sorted summary of the allocated,
freed or unfreed memory entries stored in the leak table.  Memory allocation
events can be automatically logged in the leak table by calling
@code{__mp_startleaktable()} but this behaviour can be disabled by calling
@code{__mp_stopleaktable()}.  Additional entries can be manually added to the
leak table with @code{__mp_addallocentry()} and @code{__mp_addfreeentry()}.

If you wish to write your own diagnostics to the mpatrol log file from within
your source code then you can do so with the @code{__mp_printf()} and
@code{__mp_vprintf()} functions, which are the functional equivalents of
@code{printf()} and @code{vprintf()}.  They prefix every line written to the
log file with @samp{>}, partly for making it clear where user diagnostics occur
and partly to avoid problems with external utilities that parse the mpatrol log
file.  The @code{__mp_locprintf()} and @code{__mp_vlocprintf()} functions are
equivalent functions that also display the source file and line number from
where they were called along with a stack trace, if available.

It is also possible to write out a memory dump in hexadecimal format, a stack
trace at the current point in execution and details of a memory allocation to
the log file in standard format using the @code{__mp_logmemory()},
@code{__mp_logstack()} and @code{__mp_logaddr()} functions respectively.

You can also take advantage of the @command{mpedit} command from within the
mpatrol library with the @code{__mp_edit()}, @code{__mp_list()} and
@code{__mp_view()} functions.  The first invokes a text editor on a specified
file and line number, while the second displays a context listing of a file at a
given line number.  The third function performs either or neither depending on
the setting of the @option{EDIT} or @option{LIST} options.

Finally, there are four functions which affect the mpatrol library globally.
The first, @code{__mp_check()}, allows you to force an internal check of the
mpatrol library's data structures at any point during program execution and also
to free up any out of scope memory allocations made by the @code{alloca()}
family of functions.  The @code{__mp_memorymap()} function allows you to force
the generation of a memory map at any point in your program, in much the same
way as it would normally be displayed at the end of program execution if the
@option{SHOWMAP} option was used.  The @code{__mp_summary()} function writes
library statistics to the mpatrol log file, while the @code{__mp_stats()}
function fills in a data structure with selected statistics for examination in
user code.

