@node dbmalloc, dmalloc, , Tools
@section Dbmalloc-compatible functions
@cindex Dbmalloc

This file provides Dbmalloc@footnote{Dbmalloc is copyright @copyright{}
1990-1992 Conor P. Cahill.}-compatible functions which are built on top of the
mpatrol library.  They are compatible with the last known public release of
Dbmalloc (patch level 14), but only the Dbmalloc-specific functions are defined
here, leaving the overriding of standard functions up to the mpatrol library.
As the mpatrol library does not currently override the C library string
functions and the X toolkit heap allocation functions, neither does this file.

The @code{dbmallopt()} function does not support the setting of all of the
Dbmalloc options.  In fact, most of them do not make sense when applied to the
mpatrol library.  Some of them have slightly changed behaviour due to the
mapping process and some of them cannot be implemented due to the mpatrol
library having been initialised beforehand.

The @code{malloc_dump()} function does not support the full recognition of the
@option{MALLOC_DETAIL} option in that it does not display the additional columns
and summary that the Dbmalloc library does.  This is because this would make no
sense when applied to the mpatrol library, but it does still affect whether
freed allocations are shown in the listing (although the details for such
allocations are slightly different, and there are no entries displayed for free
memory blocks).

The output for the @code{malloc_dump()} and @code{malloc_list()} functions is
almost identical to that of the Dbmalloc library except for a slight change in
the pointer format when displaying the address of each memory allocation.  The
stack information is obtained differently as well, since the mpatrol library
records symbolic stack tracebacks for each memory allocation.  As a result,
@code{malloc_enter()} and @code{malloc_leave()} do nothing and the return
address in a stack frame is displayed if no associated symbol name, file and
line number could be determined.  Parentheses are not printed at the end of
symbol names so that they can be processed properly by a C++ demangler if
necessary.  Passing a file descriptor of @samp{0} to @code{malloc_dump()} or
@code{malloc_list()} results in the output being sent to the mpatrol log file.

The @code{malloc_size()} and @code{malloc_mark()} functions do not give an error
message if the pointer passed in does not correspond to a heap allocation.
Neither of these functions automatically perform an integrity check of the
heap.  Note that the @code{malloc_chain_check()} function will never return a
non-zero value --- it always terminates with an error message in the mpatrol log
file whenever it detects heap corruption.  As a result, the
@code{malloc_abort()} function is not used.

This file is initialised via the mpatrol library's initialiser function feature,
which means that if the @code{__mp_init_dbmalloc()} function is noted by the
mpatrol symbol manager then it will be called when the mpatrol library is being
initialised.  If this feature is not supported then the @code{dbmallinit()}
function must be called as early on as possible, otherwise this file will not be
initialised until one of its functions are called.

@node dmalloc, heapdiff, dbmalloc, Tools
@section Dmalloc-compatible functions
@cindex Dmalloc

This file provides Dmalloc@footnote{Dmalloc is copyright @copyright{}
1992-2001 Gray Watson.}-compatible functions which are built on top of the
mpatrol library.  They are compatible with the 4.8.2 release of Dmalloc, but
only the Dmalloc-specific functions are defined here, leaving the overriding of
standard functions up to the mpatrol library.  As the mpatrol library does not
currently override the C library string functions, neither does this file.  In
addition, the Dmalloc distribution comes with definitions for
@code{xmemalign()}, @code{xvalloc()} and @code{xrecalloc()}, neither of which
are defined by this file or by the mpatrol library.

This module is intended to work with the existing @command{dmalloc} command,
which sets the contents of the @env{DMALLOC_OPTIONS} environment variable
according to any specified command line options.  The four documented Dmalloc
global variables are also defined, although the two address variables are not
acted upon and changing the @code{dmalloc_logpath} variable has no effect yet.
The @code{dmalloc_errno} variable is mapped onto the @code{__mp_errno} variable
and so the @code{dmalloc_strerror()} function always returns strings that are
specific to the mpatrol library.  Note that unlike the actual Dmalloc library,
this file is not threadsafe, and the @option{lockon} option has no effect.  In
addition, the @code{start} option ignores the @samp{file:line} syntax and uses
allocation indices rather than events.

The @code{dmalloc_debug()} function does not support the setting of all of the
Dmalloc flags, although this file defines preprocessor macros for each of them,
something which is not currently done in the @file{dmalloc.h} file in the
Dmalloc distribution.  In fact, many of them do not make sense when applied to
the mpatrol library.  Some of them have slightly changed behaviour due to the
mapping process and some of them cannot be implemented due to the mpatrol
library having been initialised beforehand.

The @code{dmalloc_verify()} and @code{dmalloc_examine()} functions do not give
an error message if the pointer passed in does not correspond to a heap
allocation, and the latter function does not automatically perform an integrity
check of the heap.  The @code{malloc_verify()} function has not been included in
this implementation since it is functionally identical to
@code{dmalloc_verify()}.  Note that the @code{dmalloc_verify()} function will
only ever return @code{DMALLOC_VERIFY_ERROR} if the pointer to be checked is not
null and is invalid --- it always terminates with an error message in the
mpatrol log file whenever the pointer to be checked is null and it has detected
heap corruption.

The @code{dmalloc_log_heap_map()} and @code{dmalloc_log_stats()} functions map
on to the @code{__mp_memorymap()} and @code{__mp_summary()} functions and so
have entirely different display formats.  The @code{dmalloc_log_unfreed()} and
@code{dmalloc_log_changed()} functions have similar display formats to the
original Dmalloc library, but the summary tables are displayed differently and
will display symbol names if they are available and filename and line number
information isn't.  The @code{dmalloc_message()} and @code{dmalloc_vmessage()}
functions write tracing to the mpatrol log file prefixed by three fields of
optional information, which can be controlled by the @samp{LOG_*} macros when
building this module.

This file is initialised via the mpatrol library's initialiser function feature,
which means that if the @code{__mp_init_dmalloc()} function is noted by the
mpatrol symbol manager then it will be called when the mpatrol library is being
initialised.  If this feature is not supported then the @code{dmalloc_init()}
function must be called as early on as possible, otherwise this file will not be
initialised until one of its functions are called.

@node heapdiff, mgauge, dmalloc, Tools
@section Determining heap differences
@cindex heapdiff

This file defines @code{heapdiffstart()} and @code{heapdiffend()}, which must be
called in matching pairs.  They both take a @code{heapdiff} object as their
first parameter, which must still be in scope when the matching call to
@code{heapdiffend()} is made.  The @code{heapdiff} object is initialised at the
call to @code{heapdiffstart()} and is finalised when @code{heapdiffend()} is
called.  It must not be modified in between and should be treated as an opaque
type.  @code{heapdiffend()} can only be called once per @code{heapdiff} object
before requiring that the @code{heapdiff} object be reinitialised through a
call to @code{heapdiffstart()}.

The second parameter to @code{heapdiffstart()} specifies a set of flags that can
be used to control what is written to the mpatrol log.  A list of all unfreed
memory allocations can be logged with the @code{HD_UNFREED} flag and a list of
all freed memory allocations can be logged with the @code{HD_FREED} flag,
although the latter makes use of the @option{NOFREE} option and can incur a
large performance and space penalty, and also relies on the @option{NOFREE}
option being unmodified between the calls to @code{heapdiffstart()} and
@code{heapdiffend()}.  Note that marked allocations are not normally logged but
this can be changed by adding the @code{HD_MARKED} flag.

By default, only a minimal amount of detail is logged for each allocation, but
this can be changed with the @code{HD_FULL} flag to log full details for each
allocation.  If the filename and line number for an allocation is known and the
@option{EDIT} or @option{LIST} option is being used then using @code{HD_VIEW}
will edit or list the relevant source file at the correct line number, but only
if the @option{EDIT} or @option{LIST} options are supported.

If the @code{HD_CONTENTS} flag is specified then the contents of all current
memory allocations will be written to files and then compared with their
subsequent contents when @code{heapdiffend()} is called.  If the heap is large
then this option can require a substantial amount of disk space.  All of the
allocation contents files will be deleted when the matching call to
@code{heapdiffend()} is made.

@smallexample
 1  /*
 2   * Illustrates the use of mpatrol's heap difference tool.
 3   */


 6  #include "mpatrol/heapdiff.h"


 9  int main(void)
10  @{
11      char *p, *q;
12      heapdiff h;

14      p = (char *) calloc(8, 1);
15      q = (char *) calloc(8, 1);
16      heapdiffstart(h, HD_FREED | HD_UNFREED | HD_FULL | HD_CONTENTS);
17      p = (char *) realloc(p, 16);
18      q[4] = ' ';
19      heapdiffend(h);
20      return EXIT_SUCCESS;
21  @}
@end smallexample

