@node mgauge, mtrace, heapdiff, Tools
@section Memory allocation gauge
@cindex mgauge

This file defines @code{mgaugestart()}, @code{mgaugeend()}, @code{mgaugeon()}
and @code{mgaugeoff()} which produce and control a simple memory allocation
gauge in a terminal window.  The gauge is displayed in textual form using the
standard I/O library rather than using a graphics library.  Since it is updated
in real-time, it makes no sense to send the output of the gauge to a file.  Only
one gauge can be in use at any one time.

The first argument to @code{mgaugestart()} is the filename of the file to write
the gauge to.  As mentioned before, this should be a terminal file that can be
displayed in real-time, such as @file{/dev/pts*} on UNIX systems or
@file{CON:#?} on AmigaOS.  If it is a null pointer then the standard error file
stream will be used.

The second argument to @code{mgaugestart()} specifies the character that will be
used to represent allocated memory.  If this is given as whitespace, @samp{|}
or @samp{+} then @samp{#} will be used instead.  The third argument specifies
the number of bytes that the gauge represents.  If the total allocated memory
exceeds this then @samp{+} will be appended to the gauge.  The final argument
specifies the frequency of memory allocation events at which the gauge should be
updated.  If it is specified as zero then all events will cause the gauge to be
updated.

@smallexample
 1  /*
 2   * Illustrates the use of mpatrol's memory allocation gauge
 3   * tool.
 4   */


 7  #include "mpatrol/mgauge.h"


10  int main(void)
11  @{
12      void *a[1024];
13      size_t i;

15      mgaugestart(NULL, '#', 8192, 0);
16      mgaugeon();
17      for (i = 0; i < 1024; i++)
18          a[i] = malloc(6);
19      for (i = 0; i < 1024; i++)
20          free(a[i]);
21      mgaugeoff();
22      mgaugeend();
23      return EXIT_SUCCESS;
24  @}
@end smallexample

This produces an animated gauge similar to the one displayed below.

@smallexample
0                                                           8192
| ###################################                          |
@end smallexample

