@node The mpatrol command, The mleak command, , Utilities
@section The @command{mpatrol} command
@cindex mpatrol command

A command is provided with the mpatrol distribution which can run programs that
have been linked with the mpatrol library, using a combination of mpatrol
options that can be set via the command line.  Most of these options map
directly onto their equivalent environment variable settings and exist mainly
so that the user does not have to manually change the @env{MPATROL_OPTIONS}
environment variable.

@cindex LD_PRELOAD
@cindex _RLD_LIST
The main option that is the exception to this is the @option{--dynamic} option,
which can be used to run a program under the control of the mpatrol library,
even if it wasn't originally linked with the mpatrol library.  This can only be
done on systems that support dynamic linking and where the dynamic linker
recognises the @env{LD_PRELOAD} or @env{_RLD_LIST} environment variables.  Even
then, it can only be used when the program that is being run has been
dynamically linked with the system C library, rather than statically linked.

The reason for all of these limitations is that some SVR4 UNIX platforms have a
special feature in the dynamic linker which can be told to override the symbols
from one shared library using the symbols from another shared library at
run-time.  In this case, it involves replacing the symbols for @code{malloc()},
etc.@:, in the system C library with the mpatrol versions, but only if they were
marked as undefined in the original executable file and would therefore have to
have been loaded from @file{libc.so}.

However, if a program qualifies for use with the @option{--dynamic} option, it
means that you can trace all of its dynamic memory allocations as well as
running it with any of the mpatrol library's debugging options.  This is mainly
a @emph{toy} feature which allows you to view and manipulate the dynamic memory
allocations of programs that you don't have the source for, but in theory it
could be quite useful if you need to debug a previously released executable and
are unable to recompile or relink it.  Note that if the program being run is
multithreaded then you must add the @option{--threads} option as well.

Note that the @command{mpatrol} command must be set up to use the correct
object file format access libraries that are required for your system if you
wish to use the @option{--dynamic} option.  If the mpatrol library was built
with @code{FORMAT=FORMAT_COFF} or @code{FORMAT=FORMAT_XCOFF} support then it
must be told to preload the COFF access library (normally @file{libld.so}).  If
it was built with @code{FORMAT=FORMAT_ELF32} or @code{FORMAT=FORMAT_ELF64}
support then it must be told to preload the ELF access library (normally
@file{libelf.so})@footnote{A freely available version of the ELF access library,
libelf, can be downloaded from @uref{ftp://sunsite.unc.edu/pub/Linux/libs/}.}.
If it was built with @code{FORMAT=FORMAT_BFD} support then it must be told to
preload the GNU BFD access libraries (normally @file{libbfd.so},
@file{libiberty.so} and @file{libintl.so})@footnote{The GNU BFD access library
can be downloaded from @uref{ftp://ftp.gnu.org/}.}.  However, if these libraries
only exist on your system in archive form then you must build
@file{libmpatrol.so} with these extra libraries incorporated into it so that
there are no dependencies on them at run-time.  However, there may well be
problems if the resulting shared library contains position-dependent code from
the archive libraries you incorporated.  The only way to find out is for you to
try it and see.

If you have access to the GNU linker on your system then there may be a way to
convert archive libraries into shared libraries if position-independent code is
not necessarily required for building shared libraries on your system.  If you
use the @option{--whole-archive} and @option{--shared} linker options then the
GNU linker will read the entire contents of one or more archive libraries before
writing out a shared library.  All going well, you should be able to use the new
shared library in conjunction with the @option{--dynamic} @command{mpatrol}
option.

@cindex embedded libraries
In order to build a shared version of the mpatrol library with embedded object
file format access libraries, you must first modify the @file{Makefile} you
would normally use to build the mpatrol library.  At the lines where the linker
is invoked to build the shared library, you must explicitly add any object file
format access libraries that you want to use at the end of the linker command
line.  This ensures that all references to such libraries will be resolved at
link time rather than run time.  You must then edit the file @file{src/config.h}
and remove all of the libraries that you embedded from the definitions of the
@code{MP_PRELOAD_LIBS} and @option{MP_PRELOADMT_LIBS} preprocessor macros.
Finally, rebuild the shared version of the mpatrol library and the
@command{mpatrol} command and see if your efforts were worth it.

Because the @command{mpatrol} command sets the @env{MPATROL_OPTIONS} environment
variable for each of the programs it runs, it does not affect the value of the
environment variable for the current process (except on AmigaOS and Netware
where all processes share the same environment).  However, if you wish to use
the @command{mpatrol} command to set @env{MPATROL_OPTIONS} in the current
process environment then you can use its @option{--show-env} option to help you
do so.  This option will apply all of the @command{mpatrol} command line options
to the @env{MPATROL_OPTIONS} environment variable and then display its value on
the standard output without actually running any programs.  You can then
manually set the environment variable with the output from the @command{mpatrol}
command.

@cindex .profile
@cindex ksh
@cindex bash
@cindex .cshrc
@cindex csh
@cindex tcsh
@cindex mallopt
If you wish the @env{MPATROL_OPTIONS} environment variable to be set in the
current shell process automatically with the @command{mpatrol} command then you
must use some shell trickery.  The following script excerpts can be found in
@file{extra/.profile}, @file{extra/.cshrc} and @file{extra/.gdbinit} and can be
inserted into your @command{ksh}/@command{bash}, @command{csh}/@command{tcsh}
and @command{gdb} configuration files respectively.  They each provide the
@command{mallopt} command, which takes @command{mpatrol} command options and
sets the @env{MPATROL_OPTIONS} environment variable in the current shell or
debugger process.

@smallexample
# mallopt for ksh/bash

function mallopt()
@{
    export MPATROL_OPTIONS=`mpatrol --show-env "$@@"`
    echo "$MPATROL_OPTIONS"
@}

# mallopt for csh/tcsh

alias mallopt 'setenv MPATROL_OPTIONS "`mpatrol --show-env \!*`";
               echo "$MPATROL_OPTIONS"'

# mallopt for gdb

define mallopt
printf "Enter mpatrol library options: "
shell read arg; echo set environment MPATROL_OPTIONS
                `mpatrol --show-env $arg` >/tmp/mpatrol.gdb
source /tmp/mpatrol.gdb
shell rm -f /tmp/mpatrol.gdb
show environment MPATROL_OPTIONS
end
document mallopt
Sets mpatrol library options in the current process environment.
end
@end smallexample

@node The mleak command, The mpsym command, The mpatrol command, Utilities
@section The @command{mleak} command
@cindex mleak command
@cindex mleak

Another utility program that is provided is called @command{mleak} and is
useful for detecting memory leaks in log files produced by the mpatrol library.
This program should be used if the mpatrol library could not finish writing the
log file due to abnormal program termination (which would prevent the
@option{SHOWUNFREED} option from working), but note that some of the unfreed
allocations might have been freed if the program had terminated successfully.

The @command{mleak} command scans through an mpatrol log file looking for
lines beginning with @samp{ALLOC:} and @samp{FREE:} but ignores lines beginning
with @samp{REALLOC:}, so only the @option{LOGALLOCS} and @option{LOGFREES}
options are necessary when running a program linked with the mpatrol library.
Note that as a result of this, no attempt is made to account for resizing of
memory allocations and so the total amount of memory used by the resulting
unfreed allocations may not be entirely accurate.

@cindex --ignore
This command will also read the unfreed allocations table produced by the
@option{SHOWUNFREED} option in the log file if one is present.  The entries in
the table will be compared with the currently allocated entries and will be
added if not already present.  However, this behaviour can be disabled by
supplying the @option{--ignore} option to the @command{mleak} command.

@cindex --max-stack
The @command{mleak} command can also be instructed to limit the number of lines
of stack tracing information that it will display for each unfreed memory
allocation.  This is controlled by the @option{--max-stack} option which takes
the maximum number of stack trace lines to display as an argument.  If the
number of lines is given as @samp{0} (the default) then there will be no limit
to the length of each stack trace.

The @command{mleak} command takes one optional argument which must be a valid
mpatrol log filename but if it is omitted then it will use @file{mpatrol.log} as
the name of the log file to use.  The @command{mleak} command makes two passes
over the log file so the file must be randomly-accessible.  If the filename
argument is given as @samp{-} then the standard input file stream will be used
as the log file.  Note also that the @command{mleak} command supports the
@option{--help} and @option{--version} options in common with the other mpatrol
command line tools.

@cindex condenseleaklog
Note that mpatrol patch 5 (which can be downloaded from
@uref{http://heanet.dl.sourceforge.net/sourceforge/mpatrol/mpatrol_patch5.tar.gz})
contains the source code to a FORTRAN 90 program called
@command{condenseleaklog} which offers similar facilities to the @command{mleak}
command, as well as the ability to trim and filter stack traces.

@node The mpsym command, The mpedit command, The mleak command, Utilities
@section The @command{mpsym} command
@cindex mpsym command
@cindex mpsym

Another utility program that is provided is called @command{mpsym}, which is
used to parse a log file produced by the mpatrol library and uses a debugger to
append symbol names and source level information to code addresses in stack
tracebacks.  This should be used if the @option{USEDEBUG} option is not
supported on a particular platform or does not work properly with a specific
program.  It will replace all existing symbols and source level information
associated with the stack tracebacks in the mpatrol log file and will display
the resulting log file on the standard output file stream.

The first argument to @command{mpsym} must be the filename of the executable
file that produced the mpatrol log file but if it is omitted then
@command{mpsym} will use @file{a.out} as the name of the executable file to use.
The @command{mpsym} command will read the symbol table and debugging sections
from this file in order to map the code addresses that appear in the mpatrol log
file into symbol names and source level information.  If the executable file
does not contain a symbol table then no symbol names will be available and if it
does not contain the appropriate debugging sections then no source level
information will be available either.  Obviously, if the executable file is not
the same as the one that created the mpatrol log file then the final output will
be wrong.

The second argument to @command{mpsym} must be a valid mpatrol log filename but
if it is omitted then @command{mpsym} will use @file{mpatrol.log} as the name of
the log file to use, or @file{progfile.log} if it can't find that.  The
@command{mpsym} command makes two passes over the log file so the file must be
randomly-accessable.  Note also that the @command{mpsym} command supports the
@option{--help} and @option{--version} options in common with the other mpatrol
command line tools.

@cindex --skip
If the mpatrol library cannot determine the name of a symbol for display in the
log file then it will mark the symbol as @samp{???}.  If the debugger that is
being used by @command{mpsym} also has problems determining the name of the
symbol then you can pass the @option{--skip} option to @command{mpsym} to
instruct it to skip any symbols marked as @samp{???} in the log file.

The @command{mpsym} command currently uses @command{gdb} as the debugger with
which to obtain the additional information about the code addresses in the
mpatrol log file.  It also makes use of several UNIX text processing commands,
including @command{perl} if it is installed, in order to extract information
from the debugger's output and from the log file.  As a result, the
@command{mpsym} command is only likely to work on UNIX platforms or on systems
which have the necessary commands installed.

@node The mpedit command, The hexwords command, The mpsym command, Utilities
@section The @command{mpedit} command
@cindex mpedit command
@cindex mpedit

@cindex editor
@cindex text editor
Yet another utility program that is provided is called @command{mpedit}, which
is used to invoke a text editor on a given source file and optionally jump to a
specific line number.  It is used as a support command by the mpatrol library
when the @option{EDIT} or @option{LIST} options are used but it can quite easily
be used as a command in its own right if properly configured.  Because it is a
shell script it can be easily configured to support other editors, but this
unfortunately limits it to UNIX platforms at the moment.

@cindex --source-dir
@cindex MPATROL_SOURCEPATH
The first argument to @command{mpedit} must be the filename of the source file
to be edited or listed.  If the source file does not exist then the contents of
the @env{MPATROL_SOURCEPATH} environment variable will be used to help locate
the source file, even if the filename contained an absolute or relative path
component.  This environment variable should consist of a colon-separated list
of directory names which may contain absolute paths or be relative to the
current directory; the first directory in the list will be searched first.  If
the @env{MPATROL_SOURCEPATH} environment variable is not set then only the
current directory will be searched.  You can also use the @option{--source-dir}
option to add directories to the search path used to locate the source file.
Multiple @option{--source-dir} options may be given, and each will be prepended
to the @env{MPATROL_SOURCEPATH} environment variable in the order given on the
command line.

@cindex --editor
@cindex EDITOR
If the second argument specifying the line number is omitted then it is assumed
to be @samp{1}.  The text editor will attempt to jump to the specified line
after opening the source file.  The text editor that @command{mpedit} uses is
controlled by setting the @env{EDITOR} environment variable.  This can be set to
the full pathname of the text editor to use or it can be set to the command that
would normally be used to invoke the text editor, but it cannot also contain
command line options.  You can also use the @option{--editor} option to specify
the text editor on the command line instead of using the value in the
@env{EDITOR} environment variable.

@cindex vi
@cindex vim
@cindex elvis
@cindex emacs
@cindex xemacs
@cindex pico
@cindex nano
The currently supported editors are @command{vi}, @command{vim},
@command{elvis}, @command{emacs}, @command{xemacs}, @command{pico} and
@command{nano}, and if the @env{EDITOR} environment variable is not set then the
default will be @command{vi}.  Selecting an unsupported text editor will result
in an error.  However, you can edit the @command{mpedit} file to add support for
your own favourite text editor as long as it supports a way to immediately jump
to a specific line number when it is first started up.  Note that the text
editor must also open a new window to edit the source file so that it does not
obscure any mpatrol diagnostic messages, and if it does not support this then a
new terminal window must be opened for it to use.

@cindex --listing
@cindex list
@cindex context listing
If the @option{--listing} option is given on the command line then the
@command{mpedit} command will display a context listing of the source file at
the specified line number to the standard error output stream instead of
invoking the text editor.  The listing will be annotated with line numbers and
will also show the contents of the five lines before and after the specified
line if possible.  Note also that the @command{mpedit} command supports the
@option{--help} and @option{--version} options in common with the other mpatrol
command line tools.

