After loading the program into @command{gdb}, we need to break at @code{main()}
so that we can run to a point where all of the shared library symbols have been
loaded into memory@footnote{This is really only necessary when the mpatrol
library has been built as a shared library.}.  We can then set another
breakpoint at @code{__mp_trap()} and continue until allocation 68 has been
reached.

Because the mpatrol library has not been built with debugging information in
this example we can quickly step back to the @code{strtoupper()} function since
@command{gdb} won't step through functions that have no debugging information.
We then set a watch point on address @samp{0x8071e36}, which is the address of
the memory location that has been causing the problems.  After continuing, the
debugger stops at line 46, but this is more likely to be line 45 since that is
where a zero byte is being written to@footnote{This is not necessarily the fault
of the debugger or the debugging information generated by the compiler since
on most platforms such watch points can only be caught after they occur, hence
most debuggers show the next statement to be executed rather than the current
