@node Functions 3, Functions 4, Functions 2, Functions
@section C dynamic memory alternative functions

The following 6 functions are provided as convenient alternatives to the ANSI C
dynamic memory allocation functions (although @code{strdup()} is not strictly an
ANSI C function).  They are implemented as preprocessor macro functions which
may evaluate their arguments more than once, so extra care should be taken to
avoid passing arguments with side-effects.  None of the functions return
@samp{NULL} if no memory is available and instead abort the program with a
useful error message indicating where the call to allocate memory came from and
what was being allocated.  To use these you should include the @file{mpatrol.h}
or @file{mpalloc.h} header files.

@table @asis
@findex MP_MALLOC
@item @code{void *MP_MALLOC(void *ptr, size_t count, typename type)}
Allocates @var{count} uninitialised items of type @var{type} from the heap, sets
@var{ptr} to the result and returns a suitably-cast pointer to the first item of
the allocation.  The pointer returned will be suitably aligned for holding items
of type @var{type}.  If @var{count} is @samp{0} then it will be implicitly
rounded up to @samp{1}.  If there is not enough space in the heap then the
program will be aborted after calling the allocation failure handler, which by
default writes an appropriate error message to the standard error file stream.
The allocated memory in @var{ptr} must be deallocated with @code{MP_FREE()} or
reallocated with @code{MP_REALLOC()}.

@findex MP_CALLOC
@item @code{void *MP_CALLOC(void *ptr, size_t count, typename type)}
Allocates @var{count} zero-initialised items of type @var{type} from the heap,
sets @var{ptr} to the result and returns a suitably-cast pointer to the first
item of the allocation.  The pointer returned will be suitably aligned for
holding items of type @var{type}.  If @var{count} is @samp{0} then it will be
implicitly rounded up to @samp{1}.  If there is not enough space in the heap
then the program will be aborted after calling the allocation failure handler,
which by default writes an appropriate error message to the standard error file
stream.  The allocated memory in @var{ptr} must be deallocated with
@code{MP_FREE()} or reallocated with @code{MP_REALLOC()}.

@findex MP_STRDUP
@item @code{char *MP_STRDUP(char *ptr, const char *str)}
Allocates exactly enough memory from the heap to duplicate @var{str} (including
the terminating nul character), sets @var{ptr} to the result and returns a
suitably-cast pointer to the first byte of the allocation after copying
@var{str} to the newly-allocated memory.  The pointer returned will have no
alignment constraints and can be used to store character data up to the length
of @var{str}.  If there is not enough space in the heap then the program will be
aborted after calling the allocation failure handler, which by default writes an
appropriate error message to the standard error file stream.  The allocated
memory in @var{ptr} must be deallocated with @code{MP_FREE()} or reallocated
with @code{MP_REALLOC()}.

@findex MP_REALLOC
@item @code{void *MP_REALLOC(void *ptr, size_t count, typename type)}
Resizes the memory allocation beginning at @var{ptr} to @var{count} items of
type @var{type} and returns a suitably-cast pointer to the first item of the new
allocation after copying @var{ptr} to the newly-allocated memory, which will be
truncated if @var{count} is smaller than the original number of items.  The
pointer returned will be suitably aligned for holding items of type @var{type}.
If @var{ptr} is @samp{NULL} then the call will be equivalent to
@code{MP_MALLOC()}.  If @var{count} is @samp{0} then it will be implicitly
rounded up to @samp{1}.  If @var{count} is greater than the original number of
items then the extra space will be filled with uninitialised bytes.  If there is
not enough space in the heap then the program will be aborted after calling the
allocation failure handler, which by default writes an appropriate error message
to the standard error file stream.  The allocated memory must be deallocated
with @code{MP_FREE()} and can be reallocated again with @code{MP_REALLOC()}.

@findex MP_FREE
@item @code{void MP_FREE(void *ptr)}
Frees the memory allocation beginning at @var{ptr} so the memory can be reused
by another call to allocate memory, and sets @var{ptr} to @samp{NULL} after
freeing the memory.  If @var{ptr} is @samp{NULL} then no memory will be freed.

@findex MP_FAILURE
@item @code{__mp_failhandler MP_FAILURE(__mp_failhandler func)}
Installs an allocation failure handler specifically for use with
@code{MP_MALLOC()}, @code{MP_CALLOC()}, @code{MP_STRDUP()} and
@code{MP_REALLOC()} and returns a pointer to the previously installed handler,
normally the default handler if no handler had been previously installed.  This
will be called by the above functions when there is not enough space in the heap
for them to satisfy their allocation request.  The default allocation failure
handler will terminate the program after writing an error message to the
standard error file stream indicating where the original allocation request took
place and what was being allocated.
@end table

