The following 5 functions are available as replacements for existing C++ library
functions, but the replacements in @file{mpatrol.h} will only be used if the
@code{MP_NOCPLUSPLUS} preprocessor macro is not defined.  The replacement
operators make use of the preprocessor in order to obtain source-level
information.  If this causes problems then you should define the
@code{MP_NONEWDELETE} preprocessor macro and use the @code{MP_NEW},
@code{MP_NEW_NOTHROW} and @code{MP_DELETE} macros instead of @code{new} and
@code{delete} directly.  To use these C++ features you must include
@file{mpatrol.h} before all other header files, although on UNIX and Windows
platforms (and AmigaOS when using @command{gcc}) they will be used anyway,
albeit with slightly less tracing information.

@table @asis
@findex operator new
@item @code{void *operator new(size_t size)}
Allocates @var{size} uninitialised bytes from the heap and returns a pointer to
the first byte of the allocation.  The pointer returned will be suitably aligned
for casting to any type and can be used to store data of up to @var{size} bytes
in length.  If @var{size} is @samp{0} then the memory allocated will be
implicitly rounded up to @samp{1} byte.  If there is not enough space in the
heap then either the @code{std::bad_alloc} exception will be thrown or the
null pointer will be returned and @code{errno} will be set to @code{ENOMEM} ---
the behaviour depends on whether the @emph{nothrow} version of the operator is
used.  The allocated memory must be deallocated with @code{operator delete}.

