@node Diagnostic messages, Library performance, Options, Top
@appendix Diagnostic messages
@cindex diagnostic messages
@cindex warnings
@cindex errors

The following table lists the warnings and errors that are likely to appear in
the mpatrol log file when problems with dynamic memory allocations and memory
operations occur.  Other types of warnings and errors may also appear in the log
file, but they are likely to be associated with parsing options and reading
symbols from executable files and so should be self-explanatory.

In all cases, if a warning or error is caused by one of the memory access
checking functions (invoked through the use of the @option{-fcheck-memory-usage}
option to the GNU compiler) then execution will halt regardless, despite what
the description of the diagnostic message says.

If a warning or error occurs due to a direct call to an mpatrol library function
then an attempt will be made to provide a log entry for the call.  If the
diagnostic was not caused by a normal memory allocation, reallocation or
deallocation function then the log entry will be preceded by @samp{LOG:}.  The
function type will be listed as @samp{check} if it does not fall into the normal
categories or if not enough information is available.

Note that on UNIX platforms, if the diagnostic message is caused by a line in
the program source then the @option{EDIT} and @option{LIST} options can be used
to illustrate more clearly where in the source code the warning or error
occurred.

@cindex ALLOVF
@itemize @bullet
@item
@samp{ALLOVF}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{allocation %1 has a corrupted overflow buffer at %2}
@item Type
Error
@item @samp{%1}
The pointer to the memory allocation that has a corrupted overflow buffer.
@item @samp{%2}
The pointer to the first byte of corruption in the memory allocation's overflow
buffer.
@item Cause
Something has corrupted the overflow buffer of a memory allocation and this has
been caught at the next invocation of an mpatrol function when the
@option{OFLOWSIZE} or @option{PAGEALLOC} options were used.  This particular
error message will not occur if the @option{OFLOWWATCH} option was used since
all overflow buffers will be write protected.
@item Additional
The log file entry, the library summary, the contents of the overflow buffer and
information about the original memory allocation.
@item Result
Execution terminates.
@end table

@cindex ALLZER
@item
@samp{ALLZER}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{attempt to create an allocation of size 0}
@item Type
Warning
@item Cause
A function was called to allocate memory with a size of @samp{0} when either of
the @option{CHECKALL} or @option{CHECKALLOCS} options were used.  This warning
will not occur by default as the ANSI C/C++ standards allow this behaviour, and
it is really only a portability issue.
@item Additional
The log file entry.
@item Result
The size is increased to 1 byte and execution continues.
@end table

@cindex BADALN
@item
@samp{BADALN}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{alignment %1 is not a power of two}
@item Type
Warning
@item @samp{%1}
The alignment in bytes.
@item Cause
The @code{memalign()} function was called to allocate memory with an alignment
which was not a power of two when either of the @option{CHECKALL} or
@option{CHECKALLOCS} options were used.
@item Additional
The log file entry.
@item Result
The alignment is rounded up to the nearest power of two and execution continues.
@end table

@cindex FRDCOR
@item
@samp{FRDCOR}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{freed allocation %1 has memory corruption at %2}
@item Type
Error
@item @samp{%1}
The pointer to the freed memory allocation that has been corrupted.
@item @samp{%2}
The pointer to the first byte of corruption in the freed memory allocation.
@item Cause
Something has corrupted the contents of a previously freed memory allocation and
this has been caught at the next invocation of an mpatrol function when the
@option{NOFREE} option was used.  This particular error message will not occur
if the @option{PAGEALLOC} option was used since all freed memory allocations
will be write protected and will also not occur if the @option{PRESERVE} option
was used since the free byte cannot be used to verify the freed allocation's
contents.
@item Additional
The log file entry, the library summary, the contents of the freed memory block
and information about the original memory allocation.
@item Result
Execution terminates.
@end table

@cindex FRDOPN
@item
@samp{FRDOPN}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{attempt to perform operation on freed memory}
@item Type
Error
@item Cause
A memory operation function was called to operate on a previously freed memory
allocation when the @option{NOFREE} option was used.
@item Additional
The log file entry and information about the original memory allocation.
@item Result
The memory operation fails and execution continues.
@end table

@cindex FRDOVF
@item
@samp{FRDOVF}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{freed allocation %1 has a corrupted overflow buffer at %2}
@item Type
Error
@item @samp{%1}
The pointer to the freed memory allocation that has a corrupted overflow buffer.
@item @samp{%2}
The pointer to the first byte of corruption in the freed memory allocation's
overflow buffer.
@item Cause
Something has corrupted the overflow buffer of a previously freed memory
allocation and this has been caught at the next invocation of an mpatrol
function when the @option{NOFREE} option was used in conjunction with the
@option{OFLOWSIZE} or @option{PAGEALLOC} options.  This particular error message
will not occur if the @option{OFLOWWATCH} option was used since all overflow
buffers will be write protected.
@item Additional
The log file entry, the library summary, the contents of the overflow buffer and
information about the original memory allocation.
@item Result
Execution terminates.
@end table

@cindex FRECOR
@item
@samp{FRECOR}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{free memory corruption at %1}
@item Type
Error
@item @samp{%1}
The pointer to the first byte of corruption in free memory.
@item Cause
Something has corrupted the contents of the free memory pool and this has been
caught at the next invocation of an mpatrol function.  This particular error
message will not occur if the @option{PAGEALLOC} option was used since all free
memory will be write protected.
@item Additional
The log file entry, the library summary and the contents of the free memory
block.
@item Result
Execution terminates.
@end table

@cindex FREMRK
@item
@samp{FREMRK}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{attempt to free marked allocation %1}
@item Type
Error
@item @samp{%1}
The pointer to the memory allocation that has been requested to be freed.
@item Cause
An attempt was made to free a marked memory allocation.  This is not allowed
since any memory allocations that have been marked indicate to the mpatrol
library that they should remain allocated for the duration of the program.
@item Additional
The log file entry and information about the original memory allocation.
@item Result
No memory allocation will be freed and execution continues.
@end table

@cindex FRENUL
@item
@samp{FRENUL}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{attempt to free a NULL pointer}
@item Type
Warning
@item Cause
A function was called to free an existing memory allocation with a pointer of
@samp{NULL} when either of the @option{CHECKALL} or @option{CHECKFREES} options
were used.  This warning will not occur by default as the ANSI C/C++ standards
allow this behaviour, and it is really only a portability issue.
@item Additional
The log file entry.
@item Result
No memory allocation will be freed and execution continues.
@end table

@cindex FREOPN
@item
@samp{FREOPN}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{attempt to perform operation on free memory}
@item Type
Error
@item Cause
A memory operation function was called to operate on free memory.
@item Additional
The log file entry.
@item Result
The memory operation fails and execution continues.
@end table

@cindex ILLMEM
@item
@samp{ILLMEM}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{illegal memory access at address %1}
@item Type
Error
@item @samp{%1}
The address at which the illegal memory access occurred.
@item Cause
An attempt was made to read from or write to an illegal address on systems which
have virtual memory.  This address may or may not exist in the heap, or it may
be a perfectly valid address that was misaligned and caused a bus error.  In
either case, the mpatrol library will attempt to associate the address with an
existing memory allocation.  This error may also appear instead of memory
corruption errors if the @option{PAGEALLOC} or @option{OFLOWWATCH} options were
used.
@item Additional
The library summary, information about the original memory allocation (if
possible) and the call stack of where the error occurred.
@item Result
Execution terminates.
@end table

@cindex INCOMP
@item
@samp{INCOMP}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{%1 was allocated with %2}
@item Type
Error
@item @samp{%1}
The pointer to the memory allocation that is to be resized or freed.
@item @samp{%2}
The name of the function which originally allocated the memory allocation.
@item Cause
A function was called to resize or free a memory allocation that was allocated
with a function that is incompatible with the current request.  For example,
a memory allocation which was allocated with @code{operator new} being resized
with @code{realloc()}.
@item Additional
The log file entry and information about the original memory allocation.
@item Result
The reallocation or deallocation fails and execution continues.
@end table

@cindex MAXALN
@item
@samp{MAXALN}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{alignment %1 is greater than the system page size}
@item Type
Warning
@item @samp{%1}
The alignment in bytes.
@item Cause
The @code{memalign()} function was called to allocate memory with an alignment
which was greater than the system page size when either of the @option{CHECKALL}
or @option{CHECKALLOCS} options were used.  The mpatrol library cannot currently
align memory allocations to a byte alignment over this limit, but then neither
can most other implementations.
@item Additional
The log file entry.
@item Result
The alignment is set to the system page size and execution continues.
@end table

@cindex MISMAT
@item
@samp{MISMAT}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{%1 does not match allocation of %2}
@item Type
Error
@item @samp{%1}
The pointer to the memory allocation that is to be resized or freed.
@item @samp{%2}
The pointer to the memory allocation that the mpatrol library knows about.
@item Cause
A function was called to resize or free a memory allocation that begins at a
different address from that supplied.
@item Additional
The log file entry and information about the original memory allocation.
@item Result
The reallocation or deallocation fails and execution continues.
@end table

@cindex NOTALL
@item
@samp{NOTALL}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{%1 has not been allocated}
@item Type
Error
@item @samp{%1}
The pointer to the memory allocation that is to be resized or freed.
@item Cause
A function was called to resize or free a memory allocation that has not been
allocated.  It may be that the memory allocation has just been freed, in which
case the @option{NOFREE} option should be used to provide a better diagnostic
message.
@item Additional
The log file entry.
@item Result
The reallocation or deallocation fails and execution continues.
@end table

@cindex NULOPN
@item
@samp{NULOPN}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{attempt to perform operation on a NULL pointer}
@item Type
Error
@item Cause
A memory operation function was called to operate on a @samp{NULL} pointer.  If
the length of the operation was zero then this error will only occur when the
@option{CHECKALL} or @option{CHECKMEMORY} options were used as the ANSI C/C++
standards allow this behaviour, and it is really only a portability issue.
@item Additional
The log file entry.
@item Result
The memory operation fails and execution continues.
@end table

@cindex OUTMEM
@item
@samp{OUTMEM}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{out of memory}
@item Type
Error
@item Cause
The @code{alloca()}, @code{xmalloc()} or @code{MP_MALLOC()} families of
functions were called to allocate memory, but no more memory was available to
allocate and the low-memory handler, if installed, could not free up sufficient
memory.  This error can also be caused by a call to the @code{operator new} or
@code{operator new[]} C++ operators (not the @emph{nothrow} versions) when they
would otherwise return a @samp{NULL} pointer and the mpatrol library was
compiled with a C compiler (which means that it cannot throw a
@code{std::bad_alloc} exception).
@item Additional
The library summary.
@item Result
Execution terminates.
@end table

@cindex PRVFRD
@item
@samp{PRVFRD}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{%1 was freed with %2}
@item Type
Error
@item @samp{%1}
The pointer to the memory allocation that is to be resized or freed.
@item @samp{%2}
The name of the function which originally freed the memory allocation.
@item Cause
A function was called to resize or free a memory allocation that had previously
been freed when the @option{NOFREE} option was used.
@item Additional
The log file entry and information about the original memory allocation.
@item Result
The reallocation or deallocation fails and execution continues.
@end table

@cindex RNGOVF
@item
@samp{RNGOVF}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{range [%1,%2] overflows [%3,%4]}
@item Type
Warning/Error
@item @samp{%1}
The start address of the memory region.
@item @samp{%2}
The end address of the memory region.
@item @samp{%3}
The start address of the memory allocation.
@item @samp{%4}
The end address of the memory allocation.
@item Cause
A memory operation function was called to operate on a range of memory which
overflowed the boundaries of a memory allocation.
@item Additional
The log file entry and information about the original memory allocation.
@item Result
The operation will be only be performed (and will be changed from an error to a
warning) if the @option{ALLOWOFLOW} option was used, but execution will continue
regardless.
@end table

@cindex RNGOVL
@item
@samp{RNGOVL}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{range [%1,%2] overlaps [%3,%4]}
@item Type
Warning
@item @samp{%1}
The start address of the source memory region.
@item @samp{%2}
The end address of the source memory region.
@item @samp{%3}
The start address of the destination memory region.
@item @samp{%4}
The end address of the destination memory region.
@item Cause
The @code{memcpy()} or @code{memccpy()} function was called to copy overlapping
memory regions.  This is an error on many systems and the ANSI C/C++ standards
specify that @code{memmove()} should be used instead.
@item Additional
The log file entry.
@item Result
The copy operation will still be performed but it will deal correctly with
overlapping memory regions.
@end table

@cindex RSZNUL
@item
@samp{RSZNUL}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{attempt to resize a NULL pointer}
@item Type
Warning
@item Cause
A function was called to resize an existing memory allocation with a pointer of
@samp{NULL} when either of the @option{CHECKALL} or @option{CHECKREALLOCS}
options were used.  This warning will not occur by default as the ANSI C/C++
standards allow this behaviour, and it is really only a portability issue.
@item Additional
The log file entry.
@item Result
A new memory allocation is returned and execution continues.
@end table

@cindex RSZZER
@item
@samp{RSZZER}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{attempt to resize an allocation to size 0}
@item Type
Warning
@item Cause
A function was called to resize an existing memory allocation to a size of
@samp{0} when either of the @option{CHECKALL} or @option{CHECKREALLOCS} options
were used.  This warning will not occur by default as the ANSI C/C++ standards
allow this behaviour, and it is really only a portability issue.
@item Additional
The log file entry.
@item Result
The existing memory allocation will be freed and execution continues.
@end table

@cindex STROVF
@item
@samp{STROVF}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{string %1 overflows [%2,%3]}
@item Type
Error
@item @samp{%1}
The start address of the string.
@item @samp{%2}
The start address of the memory allocation.
@item @samp{%3}
The end address of the memory allocation.
@item Cause
A string function was called to operate on a string which overflowed the
boundaries of a memory allocation.
@item Additional
The log file entry and information about the original memory allocation.
@item Result
The operation will not be performed and execution continues.
@end table

@cindex ZERALN
@item
@samp{ZERALN}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{alignment 0 is invalid}
@item Type
Warning
@item Cause
The @code{memalign()} function was called to allocate memory with an alignment
of @samp{0} when either of the @option{CHECKALL} or @option{CHECKALLOCS} options
were used.
@item Additional
The log file entry.
@item Result
The alignment is set to the default system alignment and execution continues.
@end table

@cindex ZEROPN
@item
@samp{ZEROPN}
@table @asis
@item Message
@samp{attempt to perform a zero-sized operation}
@item Type
Warning
@item Cause
A memory operation function was called with a length of zero.  This warning
will only occur when the @option{CHECKALL} or @option{CHECKMEMORY} options were
used as the ANSI C/C++ standards allow this behaviour, and it is really only a
portability issue.
@item Additional
