@cindex files questions

@enumerate 1
@item
Why is there a @file{libmpatrol.o} target in the UNIX and Amiga
@file{Makefile}s?

This is simply used to build the mpatrol library as one large object file for
full incorporation into other libraries and was used during the development of
mpatrol.  On UNIX platforms some linkers support the @option{-r} option for
combining many object files into one large object file, but this is not
universally supported, hence the reason for using the compiler instead.  Because
all of the source files are compiled at once, there may be conflicts with system
header files when @code{malloc()} and its related functions are being compiled,
which is why such an object file is not built by default.  In addition,
platforms which require the assembler routines in @file{machine.c} cannot build
the mpatrol library as one large object file from @file{library.c}.  Note that
the Windows and Netware @file{Makefile}s use @file{libmpatrol.obj}.

@cindex Subversion
@item
What are the @file{.svn} subdirectories that come with the mpatrol distribution?

SVN is short for Subversion and is a project version control system.  All of
the source files that comprise an mpatrol release are stored in a central
Subversion repository so that previous releases can be easily retrieved, but
the Subversion system needs to have a way of determining the versions of
currently checked-out files, hence the @file{.svn} subdirectories.

@item
Why does the @command{mpsym} command not work for me?

Firstly, you have to ensure that you have compiled all relevant object files
with debugging information enabled (usually by adding an option to the compiler
command line).  The file and line number information will hopefully then appear
in the log file for all symbols that have associated debugging information when
you run the @command{mpsym} command on the log file.  Alternatively, it could be
that your system does not have @command{gdb} or any of the required UNIX text
processing tools installed, in which case you might want to try installing them.

@item
How can I customise the @command{mpedit} command if I do not have the
appropriate permissions to edit the file that was installed on my system?

You just need to take a copy of the installed @command{mpedit} command and place
it somewhere that will be picked up earlier on your command search path.  You
can then edit your copy of the file and add support for your favourite text
editor.

@cindex mupdate
@cindex ChangeLog
@cindex NEWS
@cindex VERSION
@item
What does the @command{mupdate} shell script do?

This is for my use in order to automate every new release of mpatrol.  You
should never need to run this script and it should not be installed anywhere on
your system.  This script also uses and modifies the @file{VERSION} file and
updates the @file{NEWS} and @file{ChangeLog} files.
@end enumerate

